     <country-head>Bosnia and Herzegovina</country-head>
     <heading>Geography</heading>
     <alt-heading type="SECTION-LONG-UPPERCASE" usage="casee">Bosnia and Herzegovina</alt-heading>
     <alt-heading type="COUNTRY-SHORT-TITLECASE" usage="casee">Geography</alt-heading>
     <gen-section print-style="COLUMN" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="GEN-SECTREF">
          <heading>Physical Features</heading>
          <p id="BA.GEOG.1">Bosnia and Herzegovina is a mountainous territory with only about 20&#160;km (12 miles) of coastline, which is of little maritime significance. Roughly triangular in shape, the country juts into Croatia, which forms its western border (extending from north-west to south-east, along the Dinaric Alps) and its northern border. Serbia lies to the east (there is a short border with the province of Vojvodina in the north-east) and Montenegro to the south-east. The total area of the country is 51,209 sq&#160;km (19,772 sq&#160;miles).</p>
          <p id="BA.GEOG.2">The ancient province of Bosnia is roughly the territory bounded by the Sava, Drina and Una rivers. Along the Sava, which forms the northern border, there are fertile lowlands. The chief town, and the country’s capital, is Sarajevo, which is in the south, near the headwaters of the River Bosna (from which the province acquired its name). Herzegovina (only 18% of the total area) occupies the south of the country, with the Dalmatian coastal strip, in Croatia, to the south-west and Montenegro to the south-east. Its chief town is Mostar. Most of Herzegovina is mountainous and infertile, but there are fruitful valleys.</p>
          <p id="BA.GEOG.3">Under the terms of the General Framework Agreement for Peace in Bosnia and Herzegovina, agreed at Dayton, Ohio, USA, in 1995, most of the country comprises two entities: the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina and Republika Srpska. The Federation occupies the west and centre of the country, its territory tapering north-eastwards, with a road linking it to the eastern enclave of Goražde; there is also a northern exclave, Posavina Canton, located around the town of Orašje. Republika Srpska comprises most of the remaining 49% of the country, its territory concentrated along the eastern border, including southern (or `Old’) Herzegovina, and in the north of the country, around Banja Luka and the Bosnian Krajina. The district of Brčko, in the north-east, forms a part of neither entity.</p>
     </gen-section>
     <gen-section print-style="COLUMN" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="GEN-SECTREF">
          <heading>Climate</heading>
          <p id="BA.GEOG.4">The largely mountainous territory of Bosnia and Herzegovina has a continental climate, although this is moderated with proximity to the coast. The hinterland of the Dalmatian coast (itself in Croatia) and the territory around Bosnia and Herzegovina’s small coastal town of Neum has a Mediterranean climate.</p>
