     <gen-section print-style="COLUMN" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="GEN-SECTREF">
          <heading>Population</heading>
          <p id="BA.GEOG.5">According to projections by the United Nations, the population numbered 3,210,848 at mid-2023, giving a density of 62.7 per sq&#160;km. The Bosnian Muslims (Bosniaks) are a Slavic people, who adopted Sunni Islam during Ottoman rule. In 1961 they were accorded the status of an ethnic group, being recognized as a Yugoslav national unit in 1968, and they were the largest single group in Bosnia and Herzegovina. In 1991 they comprised 43.5% of the total population. At that time Serbs accounted for 31.2% of the population and Croats for 17.4%. At the census of 2013, Bosniaks accounted for 50.1% of the population, Serbs 30.8% and Croats 15.4%. Religious affiliation is roughly equated with ethnicity. The Croats and Serbs are Christians, the former adhering to the Roman Catholic Christians, and the latter to the Eastern Orthodox Church. The mutually comprehensible languages of Bosnian, Croatian and Serbian (all of which were referred to as variants of Serbo-Croatian during the Yugoslav period) have equal status in both the Federation and Republika Srpska; Bosnian and Croatian are written in the Latin script, while Serbian is more commonly and traditionally written in Cyrillic.</p>
          <p id="BA.GEOG.6">
      Sarajevo is the country’s largest city, with a population of 275,524, according to results of the census of 2013. It is the capital of the country and of the Federation
      
       and, 
      <i>de jure</i>
      , of Republika Srpska. The Serb-inhabited outskirts of the city are administered separately, within Republika Srpska, as the city of Istočno (East) Sarajevo, which had a population of 61,516. The country’s second city, Banja Luka (with a population of 185,042), is the de facto capital of Republika Srpska. Mostar (with an estimated population of 105,797, with large populations of both Bosniaks and Croats, is the chief town in the main area of Croat settlement. Other important towns in the Federation include Tuzla, in the north-east (with a population of 110,979) and Zenica (110,663). Important towns in Republika Srpska include: Bijeljina (with a population of 107,715), in the north-east; Prijedor (89,397), in the Bosnian Krajina; and Doboj (71,441).
    </p>
     </gen-section>
